> I suspect we should keep it for now - see how it goes, revisit for API 8.

I would rather remove it, to avoid causing unnecessary steps when migrating to API 8 as an API user.

AFAICT the service currently has two functions:

1. token or alias to Parser mapping
2. utility methods to create `PlaceholderTexts`

Regarding the first point: We should encourage users to use the original ids instead of aliases, especially since the parameters are parser dependent. If we discover an actual need for it we can still add it later.
Regarding the second point: Static helper methods would probably do the same job.

What I don't like about the current approach is, that I need a `PlaceholderParser` to create a `PlaceholderText` but I there is a `parse(PlaceholderText)` method on the parser. What is supposed to happen if I create the PlaceholderText with parser A and pass it to parser B?

To avoid this problem you should change the PlaceholderParser to only have the following method or no such method at all:

`newTextBuilder() : PlaceholderTextBuilder`


-------------------------------------------
<details>
<summary>
How about a structure like this: (Click to expand)
</summary>

- `PlaceholderParser<T extends PlaceholderText.Builder> extends CatalogType`
  - `newTextBuilder() : T`
- `PlaceholderText extends TextRepresentable`
  - `toText() : Text`

The `PlaceholderParser` is a catalog type, that does not contain any logic except creating a new builder.
By default, the PlaceholderText/Builder "supports" some basic options (those that are currently specified in the `PlaceholderText.Builder`), but the PlaceholderParser might as well return custom subclasses.
Templating plugins can then inspect those custom implementations for attributes to set or they just use the default ones.
Plugin developers that invoke a specific parser (e.g. via catalog class) can use the setters to set specific values directly without guessing how to set it. E.g. set the format via `setFormat("#,###.00")` instead of `setArgumentString("format=#,###.00")`.

Example:

````java
interface PlaceholderParser<T extends PlaceholderText.Builder > extends CatalogType {

    Class<T> getTextBuilderClass(); // <-- Optional, helper for templating plugin introspection (It would return interface class instead of impl class)

    T newTextBuilder();

}
````

````java
interface PlaceholderText extends TextRepresentable {

    interface Builder<T extends Builder> extends ResetableBuilder {

        T setAssociatedObject(Object object);

        T setArgumentString(String argument);

        PlaceholderText build();

    }

}
````

````java
final class PlaceholderParsers {

    public static final PlaceholderParser<BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder> BALANCE = ...;

}
````

````java
interface BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder extends PlaceholderText.Builder<BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder> {

    BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder setCurrencyId(String currencyId);

    BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder setCurrency(Currency currency);

    BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder setAddSendWithdrawTextButton(boolean add);

    [...]

}
````
````java
class BalancePlaceholderTextBuilderImpl extends BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder {

    private Supplier<Currency> currencySupplier = () -> null;

    BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder setCurrencyId(String currencyId) {
        currencySupplier  = () -> toCurrency(currencyId);
        return this;
    }

    BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder setCurrency(Currency currency) {
        currencySupplier  = () -> currency;
        return this;
    }

    BalancePlaceholderTextBuilder setArgumentString(String argument) {
        argument.splitAsStream(";")
                .map(s -> s.split("="))
                .filter(s ->  s[0] == "currency")
                .forEach(s -> setCurrencyId(s[1]));
        return this;
    }
}
````

````java
class BalancePlaceholderText extends PlaceholderText {

    Text toText() {
        try{
             Currency currency = currencySupplier.get().orElse(economyService.getDefaultCurrency()):
             return Text.of(formatter.format(economyService.getBalance(getAssociatedObject(), currency)));
        } catch (Exception e) {
            return Text.EMPTY;
        }
    }

    String getArgumentString() {
        return joiner(";")
                .addIfSet("currency", currencySupplier)
                .addIfSet("format", formatter.getFormat()):
}
````

````java
// From code (known parser in dependency)
PlaceholderParsers.BALANCE.newTextBuilder()
        .setAccountOwner(player)
        .setFormat("#,###.00")
        .toText();
// From template/config (plugin X)
messages.show_current_player_balance=You have ${foobar:balance;format="#,###.00"}.
registry.getCatalog(PlaceholderParser.class, "foobar:balance")
        .setAssociatedObject(player)
        .setArgumentString("format="#,###.00") // Requires lookup from documentation
        .toText();
````
<details>

I actually have one more point to make that came to mind later, rather than edit the above, I'll add it as another comment:

> Plugin developers that invoke a specific parser (e.g. via catalog class) can use the setters to set specific values directly without guessing how to set it.

That would require a dep on the plugin in question. In that scenario, either the parser class can be referenced directly and if a builder is supplied, it can discover it _without_ needing to rely on Sponge. So parsers really should not enforced to build `PlaceholderText`s at all, such a method is pointless.

What I will probably do is separate out the text such that we have a `PlaceholderContext` that holds the associated object and string, and the `PlaceholderText` will be the following:

```java
interface PlaceholderText extends TextRepresentable {

    PlaceholderContext getContext();

    PlaceholderParser getParser();

    Text toText() { // impl will be something like
        getParser().parse(getContext());
     }
}
```

It changes very little, but will mean that the context has no dep on the parser whatsoever. I will not change anything else to complicate matters for templating systems or plugins that want to provide a simple placeholder - they can do it in one class or with our builder.

---

Do remember what this placeholder system is all about. It is about unifying all the current Placeholder based chat systems so that plugins can just provide placeholders and we can all use them. This is intended as a _simple_ way to provide a placeholder with a simple way for templating engines to interface with it without having to understand parsers. This puts the burden of correctly filling out the argument string on the user, as it should be, to make it simple for templating engines to do what they do best, provide a template.

If you want to get a text outside of this with a parameter builder, it might be worth asking the plugin developer to provide a builder outside of the parser altogether. That, however, is outside of the scope of what this will do.

