In consideration of https://github.com/SpongePowered/SpongeAPI/issues/1824, I've elected to take the chance to ~royally break~ refactor the hierarchy of `Value` and the subclasses of such. 

The design for the new classes so to speak is to have separated the accessors from mutator methods. Accessor methods are available on the base classes (so, you have some list methods available in `ListValue`), but the mutator methods and modifier methods are available depending on whether you have a `Mutable` or `Immutable` subclass of the overall target.

The old usage  of values was something like so:

```java
final BlockState state = BlockTypes.STONE.getDefaultState();
final Optional<StoneType> stoneType = state.get(Keys.STONE_TYPE);
    // Up until this point, we're fine. This next line will cause a class cast exception
final Value<StoneType> value = state.getValue(Keys.STONE_TYPE).orElseThrow(() -> new IllegalStateException("Stone should have stone type")); 
// This won't work as the value is already an immutable value instance, throws an exception in the line above.
final ImmutableValue<StoneType> stoneTypeImmutableValue = value.asImmutable();
```

The biggest problem here is that the returned class type of a BlockState would not be a `Value`, but an `ImmutableValue`. Neither classes are interchangeable, let alone usable in this case because the returned value would still end up being invalid and cause a `ClassCastException`.

Now, what this refactoring intends to replace that with is:
```java
final BlockState state = BlockTypes.STONE.getDefaultState();
final Optional<StoneType> stoneType = state.get(Keys.STONE_TYPE);
final Value<StoneType> stoneTypeValue = state.getValue(Keys.STONE_TYPE).orElseThrow(() -> new IllegalStateException("Stone should have stone type!"));
final Value.Immutable<StoneType> stoneTypeImmutable = stoneTypeValue.asImmutable();
final Value.Mutable<StoneType> stoneTypeMutable = stoneTypeValue.asMutable();
```

The beauty of the new way is that you don't have to worry about whether it's mutable or not, since you can declare it as such and it will **work** without issue.

I'm expanding the PR a little to improve some more parts about the Values and how they are used, but this is it for now.

