This PR adds a key bindings api that will allow plugin developers to create custom key bindings. The api is always available, on both client and server versions, this is because the server will send packets to register the key bindings on joining the server and cleaned up afterwards, but this is a implementation detail.

I am not sure if I should have waited for the client-phase-1, but since the client isn't required for players to join and the api impl does not require any client. The impl will only send packets to the client and recieve them back.

I am also also only going to implement this in the minecraft versions 1.9+, depending on which version should be supported at that time.

There is already a small LiteLoader mod I made for the client features, it won't work in combination with  Forge. Most of the keyboard code will be able to be reused for the Forge implementation.

Test plugin:

``` java
@Plugin(id = "keyboardtest")
public class TestKeyboardPlugin {

    @Listener
    public void onGameInit(GameInitializationEvent event) {
        final KeyBinding myTestKey = KeyBinding.builder()
                .displayName(Text.of("Test Binding"))
                .category(KeyCategories.GAMEPLAY)
                .listener(InteractKeyEvent.Press.class, e -> e.getTargetEntity().sendMessage(Text.of("Ow, that hurt...")))
                .build(this, "test");
        Sponge.getRegistry().register(KeyBinding.class, myTestKey);
        final KeyCategory testCategory = KeyCategory.builder()
                .title(Text.of("My Test Category"))
                .build(this, "test_category");
        Sponge.getRegistry().register(KeyCategory.class, testCategory);
        final KeyBinding myOtherTestKey = KeyBinding.builder()
                .displayName(Text.of("Other Test Binding"))
                .category(testCategory)
                .context(KeyContexts.IN_GAME)
                .listener(InteractKeyEvent.Press.class, e -> e.getTargetEntity().sendMessage(Text.of("And... Nothing...")))
                .listener(InteractKeyEvent.Release.class, e -> e.getTargetEntity().sendMessage(Text.of("Nope still nothing...")))
                .build(this, "other_test");
        Sponge.getRegistry().register(KeyBinding.class, myOtherTestKey);
        final KeyBinding contextTestKey = KeyBinding.builder()
                .displayName(Text.of("Context Test Binding"))
                .category(testCategory)
                .context(KeyContexts.INVENTORY)
                .listener(InteractKeyEvent.Press.class, e -> e.getTargetEntity().playSound(
                        SoundTypes.UI_BUTTON_CLICK, e.getTargetEntity().getLocation().getPosition(), 0.5))
                .build(this, "context_test");
        Sponge.getRegistry().register(KeyBinding.class, contextTestKey);
    }

    @Listener
    public void onRegisterKeyBinding(RegisterKeyBindingsEvent event) {
        System.out.println(String.format("onRegisterKeyBinding: %s keyBindings, player %s",
                event.getKeyBindings().size(), event.getTargetEntity().getName()));
    }

    @Listener(order = Order.EARLY)
